title: For Sale/Trade:  Pulsar HD19s Handheld Thermal Unit
postcontent:
Up for sale is a nearly new Pulsar Quantum HD19s thermal unit. It was purchased new in September and has only seen less than 5 hours of use since. It’s in perfect condition. 

I’ve owned or used some of the other thermals in this price range (Eotech X320, ATN OTS-X) and the Pulsar blows them away in my opinion. The clarity is really very impressive and its super easy to operate. The other thing that is a huge plus for the Pulsar Quantum line is the independent manual gain and brightness controls. None of the others in the price range have this feature. I didn’t realize how beneficial this feature was until I used some other units. In fact I originally had another HD19s and sold it because I got a great deal on the more expensive Eotech X320. It didn’t hold a candle to the Pulsar so I so wound up selling it and getting this one. 

The only reason I’m selling is I’m moving to the exact same unit except with more magnification (HD38). 

The unit comes with the original purchase documentation, manual, all cables, etc., plus a bonus; it has a Pulsar hard case, very similar to a pelican. 

Link for specs:

http://pulsarnv.com/pl77313.html

Due to ITAR regulations you must be a U.S. Citizen to own or use a thermal device. 

It's hard to get good photos through any NV unit, however, there are several youtube videos that offer a pretty good representation of the image quality. If you have questions, please don’t hesitate to ask. Thanks for looking!

title: For Trade:  1991 GMC Sonoma 4.3L Stakeback Auto 2wd
postcontent:
Hi, thanks for looking!

For trade today is a 1991 GMC Sonoma pickup truck with stakeback bed.  This truck features a powerful 4.3L V6 TBI engine, automatic transmission with overdrive, and a mount for a towing ball.  Recent new parts include the battery, fuel pump, water pump, upper control arms, and more.  It has approximately 161,000 miles.

This is a very reliable truck!  Tires and exhaust are good, all the glass is good, and there is not much noteworthy rust except around a wheel well.

It's a quirky truck that has its nuisance problems, which are easy to fix but not really very pressing.  I removed the stereo and planned to replace it, but I should still have all of the parts to put the old one back in.  The headliner is removed (which I actually prefer).  The heater blower switch is dirty.  The driver's side mirror needs a cheap set screw, which I never got around to adding.  The turn signal arm doesn't automatically click back off after completing a turn.  The left side of the rear bumper is a little bent from where my friend borrowed my truck and then proceeded to back into my Shelby with it.  >_<  These minor issues are easily ignored.  It's a truck!

The stakeback conversion makes for a heavy duty 5'6" x 8' flat bed area, and the side rails and box are attached with simple bolts and wingnuts.  You can even leave just the box and the flat bed for carrying tools and sheets of lumber, for instance.  It's a simple modular design, so if you can cut and drill, you can make new things to bolt on.  The pressure treated lumber has dried, so it could use some touch-up and a deck treatment.

Thanks for looking, and if you have any questions, please feel free to ask!

title: For Sale:  AR-15 dual magazine pouches
postcontent:
I've been making gear for my co-workers and myself for a few years.  I just recently started selling gear on the internet.  If you have something you would like custom made, please don't hesitate to contact me.  I mainly do chest rigs, MOLLE pouches, slings, dog leashes, and riggers belts, but can do other stuff as well.

Up for sale are coyote tan dual AR-15 magazine pouches made by me.  Price is $15 if we meet face to face, or $22 if I ship it.  If I ship it, I prefer you purchase it through my Etsy shop to protect us both.  (https://www.etsy.com/listing/218024774/ar-15-dual-magazine-pouch-coyote-brown?)  

This is a heavy duty dual magazine pouch for AR-15 and similarly sized magazines. This pouch is made in the USA, with materials that are made in the USA. All materials are mil-spec, and Berry Amendment compliant.

The shell of this pouch is made from a double layer of 3" nylon webbing that conforms to mil-spec 17337. This provides a great amount of strength and abrasion resistance. The body is made from 1000 Denier Cordura, which is the same material used to make plate holders for body armor.

This will fit two AR-15 magazines, both standard aluminum and Magpul polymer magazines in either the bullet-up or bullet-down configuration.

The flap of the pouch secures to the body of the pouch with a generous portion of hook and loop fabric. With one or two magazines inside this pouch, the allowance of the hook and loop will keep your magazines tight to your kit.

On the back of this magazine pouch is a 5 inch PALS strip for attachment to MOLLE gear. Two black MALICE clips are included.

This item was sewn on an industrial sewing machine using size 92 bonded nylon thread. The industry standard is only size 69 bonded nylon thread. Even though it is more time consuming to change bobbins, and more costly, I choose to use a stronger thread because I make gear that people depend their life on.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Stoeger Cougar Compact
postcontent:
I have a Stoeger Cougar compact I'm interested in trading.

 If you aren't familiar with the Cougar design it is the precursor to the Beretta PX4 and uses a rotating barrel action to improve accuracy and lower recoil. Identical to the Beretta Cougar aside from the name on the slide; Beretta transferred the tooling and manufacturing equipment to Stoeger, Stoeger being a subdivision of Benelli, which is in turn owned by Beretta. Has the same manual of arms as a Beretta 92/M9, so its a great choice if you're looking for a more compact version for carry.

 Has some light holster wear from being carried but overall is in good shape, bought new about two months ago and only has about 200 rounds through it. Will come with two 13 round magazines. Depending on what you have I can also include an extra 15 round magazine (modified Beretta 92 mag) and I have a fair amount of 9mm ammo.

First choice would be a Springfield XD9 or Ruger SR9, but would consider similar 9mm's in this size range.  Only looking for 9mm's though, and no Taurus or Kel Tecs please.
